Adds a lemma implicit in the proof of Bourbaki, TVS IV.24, §5 Theorem 1 (Banach-Dieudonneé theorem)

(See also Lemma 12.2 from Conway, A Course in Functional Analysis for the Banach space version).

---

Should this be `@[simp]`? I'm not sure, so feel free to argue if you disagree. If it were, then `mem_polar_singleton` is provable `by simp`.
On balance, I think so, but I may not be the best judge of what makes a good simp lemma.

or `sInter_polar_eq_closedBall`, if you want.
```suggestion
theorem sInter_polar_finite_reciprocal_closedBall {𝕜 E : Type*} [RCLike 𝕜] [NormedAddCommGroup E]
```

If you use `ext` to begin with, then you only need to do the `simp` once.
```suggestion
  ext x
  simp only [Set.sInter_image, Set.mem_setOf_eq, Set.mem_iInter, and_imp]
  refine ⟨fun hx a ha ↦ ?_, fun hx F _ hF₂ => polar_antitone _ hF₂ hx⟩
  simpa [mem_polar_singleton] using hx _ (Set.finite_singleton a) (Set.singleton_subset_iff.mpr ha)
```
